1️⃣ Programming Language

Python 3.x (free, easy for beginners, widely supported)

Download: https://www.python.org/downloads/

Features needed: classes (OOP), lists, dicts, random, print/logging

2️⃣ IDE / Code Editor

VS Code (free, lightweight, supports Python)

Download: https://code.visualstudio.com/

Extensions:

Python extension (official)

Pylance (intellisense)

Code Runner (optional, run Python quickly)

Alternative: PyCharm Community Edition (free)

3️⃣ Simulation / Agent Frameworks

Option 1 – Simple Python simulation (offline)

Use 2D grid + classes

Only Python standard libraries: random, time, copy, math

Option 2 – Agent-based library (optional for polish)

Mesa → free, Python-based, supports agents & grid simulation

Docs: https://mesa.readthedocs.io/

Optional agent framework (offline demo friendly)

Microsoft AutoGen (can run locally, optional)

LangChain local setup (offline mode)

Vercel AI SDK (offline dev possible)

4️⃣ MCP Protocol (Mandatory)

MCP Python SDK → free, required for drone-agent communication

GitHub: https://github.com/modelcontextprotocol/python-sdk

Use MCP to:

Expose drone tools: move_to(), get_battery_status(), thermal_scan()

Allow agent to dynamically discover drones

5️⃣ Visualization Tools (Optional but recommended)

Console output / ASCII grid → no cost

Use print() + emojis or symbols for drones 🛸 and survivors 🧍

Tkinter → simple free GUI for Python

Standard Python library → no installation needed

Matplotlib → optional grid visualization

pip install matplotlib (free)

6️⃣ Version Control & Project Management

Git → free, local version control

Download: https://git-scm.com/

GitHub → optional remote backup (free public/private repos)

https://github.com/

7️⃣ Random Data / Simulation Inputs

Python random module → generate disaster maps & survivor positions

numpy → optional, for grid math & distance calculation

copy → optional, to duplicate grid state

8️⃣ Documentation / References (All Free)

MCP docs → https://modelcontextprotocol.io/introduction

Mesa agent-based simulation docs → https://mesa.readthedocs.io/

Hackathon Case Booklet (provided by USM) → contains all requirements

9️⃣ Optional Polishing / Demo Tools (Free)

Colorama → colored terminal output (pip install colorama)

PrettyTable → nice table display for grid or logs (pip install prettytable)

Jupyter Notebook → optional interactive demo (pip install notebook)

10️⃣ Summary / Minimum Required Stack

You absolutely can do this with:

Python 3.x

VS Code

MCP Python SDK

random + print for simulation

Optional: Mesa / Tkinter / Colorama

Everything else is optional for polish or better visualization.
💡 No paid AI APIs or cloud services needed → fully offline + zero cost